ent political cultures, and how the ideological domination of oppressed classes can shatter.This work is a new and vital chapter in the growing literature on the formation of social movements. It chronicles the transformation of Peru's poor from a culture of deference and clientelism in the late 1960s to a population mobilized for radical political action today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConflits sociauxxPérou. 0aConflits sociauxxPérou. 0aMouvements sociauxxPérou. 0aMouvements sociauxxPérou. 0aPauvres en milieu urbainxActivité politiquexPérou. 0aPauvres en milieu urbainxActivité politiquexPérou. 0aSocial conflictxPeru. 0aSocial conflictzPeru. 0aSocial movementsxPeru. 0aSocial movementszPeru. 0aUrban poorxPolitical activityxPeru. 0aUrban poorxPolitical activityzPeru. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh  a20th century peruvian history.  acivilian rule.  aclass consciousness.  aclass difference.  aclientelism.  acontemporary peru.  adeference.  aethnography.  ahegemony.  aideology.  aindependent.  alatin american history.  alower class politics.  amass public.  anation state.  aoligarchy.  aoppressed classes.  aoppression.  aparticipant observation.  aperu.  aperuvian history.  apolitical culture.  apolitics.  apoor people.  apopular culture.  apoverty.  aradical political thought.  aradical politics.  ashantytown.  asocial activists.  asocial movements.  astate.  aurban poor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020023440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520916234?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520916234423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520916234/or